.SH "NAME"
"IO::Async::SSLStream" \- read and write buffers around an SSL connection
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
This subclass of IO::Async::Stream provides support for using an \s-1SSL\s0
connection, as created by IO::Async::SSL's \f(CW\*(C`SSL_connect\*(C'\fR or \f(CW\*(C`SSL_listen\*(C'\fR
extension methods. After one of these methods has provided a socket handle, it
should be wrapped in an IO::Async::SSLStream object to provide the usual
\&\f(CW\*(C`on_read\*(C'\fR callback.
.PP
It provides no extra methods and consumes no extra configuration parameters;
treat it the same as a regular \f(CW\*(C`IO::Async::Stream\*(C'\fR object.
.PP
See the main IO::Async::SSL documentation for an example of its use.
.SH "BUGS"
.IX Header "BUGS"
.IP "\(bu" 4
Currently, this subclass does not completely handle the \f(CW\*(C`autoflush\*(C'\fR configure
option. It is possible for the \f(CW\*(C`SSL_write(3ssl)\*(C'\fR call to fail with \f(CW\*(C`EAGAIN\*(C'\fR
and \f(CW\*(C`SSL_WANT_READ\*(C'\fR, indicating that it wishes to read (perhaps to obtain
fresh keys from the server). In this case, the subclass will not correctly
poll for readability and retry the write operation. This bug does not occur
with regular \f(CW\*(C`write\*(C'\fR with \f(CW\*(C`autoflush\*(C'\fR turned off.
